## Root cause (from hands-on evidence)

# Surprises — L-capstone CRUD API with Middleware Stack

All observations are grounded in what actually happened during the live build.

---

## 1. `bearerGuard` must precede `zValidator` in the chain to get 401 before body parsing

When the middleware order was `zValidator → bearerGuard`, an unauthenticated POST with
an invalid body returned `400` (zod rejection) rather than `401` (auth rejection). The
guard and the validator both run as middleware and the first one to short-circuit wins.

The correct order is: `app.post('/items', bearerGuard, zValidator('json', schema), handler)`.
This ensures auth failures fire before body parsing, which is the correct security shape —
you don't leak schema information to unauthenticated callers.

---

## 2. `DELETE` with no body must return `new Response(null, { status: 204 })` — `c.body(null, 204)` also works

`c.json(null, 204)` works but sends `content-type: application/json` with a null-serialized
body. The cleaner form is `new Response(null, { status: 204 })` which sends no body at all.
Both return `res.status === 204` from `app.request()`. The test asserts only the status code.

---

## 3. `jose` import pattern in Node ESM middleware — dynamic import not needed

Because the test file is a `.mjs` module (or `"type":"module"` package), top-level
`import { SignJWT, jwtVerify } from 'jose'` works at module load time. An earlier version
of `bearerGuard` used a dynamic `import('jose')` inside the handler to work around a
CJS/ESM split — that is not needed in a pure ESM context and adds unnecessary indirection.

---

## 4. CORS `origin` matching is exact-string, not wildcard

Setting `cors({ origin: 'https://example.com' })` means only requests with
`Origin: https://example.com` receive `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://example.com`.
A request with `Origin: https://other.com` gets no ACAO header — Hono does not reflect
arbitrary origins or fall back to `*` when a specific string is configured.

This is the intended secure behavior but can surprise developers who expect reflection.

---

## 5. `secureHeaders()` import path is `hono/secure-headers`, not `hono/middleware`

The import `import { secureHeaders } from 'hono/middleware'` fails at runtime with a module
resolution error. The correct path is `hono/secure-headers`. This matches the spike findings
and is consistent across Hono v4.

---

## 6. In-memory `store` shared across the module requires `beforeEach(resetStore)`

Because `store` and `nextId` are module-level variables and the `app` instance is built once
at module load, any test that mutates the store will bleed into subsequent tests. `beforeEach`
with `resetStore()` is essential for test isolation. Without it, IDs increment across tests
and assertions on `id === 1` fail in later tests.

---

## 7. Exit code redirect discipline: `> file 2>&1; echo "EXIT=$?" >> file` — not a pipe

`node --test capstone.test.mjs | tee out.txt` would always report exit code 0 (the tee
process's exit code) even when 

