## Root cause (from hands-on evidence)

# Surprises & Gotchas — L-capstone Async Job Pipeline

All discovered live against `127.0.0.1:54322` (pgmq 1.5.1 / pg_cron 1.6.4 / pg_net 0.20.0 /
pgcrypto 1.3 on `supabase/postgres:17.6.1.106`).

## 1. `pg` is CommonJS — ESM named imports throw

`import { Client } from "pg"` fails under Node ESM with:

```
SyntaxError: The requested module 'pg' does not provide an export named 'Client'
```

Fix: default-import then destructure.

```js
import pg from "pg";
const { Client } = pg;
```

(`pg@8.13.1` has no ESM named exports; this bites every `"type":"module"` POC.)

## 2. `DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS … ON <table>` still requires the table to exist

On a clean DB, `drop trigger if exists au_d07_cap_enqueue on au_d07_cap_documents` raises
**42P01 `relation "au_d07_cap_documents" does not exist`** — the `IF EXISTS` guards the *trigger*,
not the *table*. So an idempotent teardown that drops the trigger before the table blows up on the
first run. Fix: drop the **table with `CASCADE`** (which removes its triggers) instead of a standalone
trigger drop, or guard the trigger drop on table existence. This POC's `teardownPipeline` drops the
table cascade first.

## 3. The trigger enqueues *synchronously inside the INSERT*

`pgmq.metrics(queue).queue_length` is already `3` the instant after inserting 3 rows, **before any
worker runs**. That is exactly what makes the RED test meaningful: enqueue is immediate and durable,
but processing is deferred to the worker. (It also means a failing AFTER INSERT trigger would roll back
the INSERT — keep trigger bodies cheap; do the heavy work in the worker, never the trigger.)

## 4. Per-message error isolation needs an inner `BEGIN…EXCEPTION` block

A naive processor that loops over `pgmq.read(...)` and lets any error propagate will abort the whole
batch — one poison message blocks every sibling in the same `read`. Wrapping each message in its own
`BEGIN … EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN …` block isolates the failure: the bad row is marked
`status='error'` (with `SQLERRM` captured), the good rows in the same batch still reach `done`, and the
worker function returns normally instead of crashing. **Verified live (R2):** good id=5 → `done`,
bad id=6 (NULL content) → `status='error'`, `error='null content for doc 6'`, batch did not abort.

Note: on error this POC leaves the message on the queue (its 30s visibility timeout lapses → it becomes
retryable). If you do NOT want infinite retries, read `read_ct` from `pgmq.read` and `pgmq.archive`
(dead-letter) the message past a threshold rather than re-reading it forever.

## 5. pg_cron `'5 seconds'` (sub-minute) is accepted and really fires

pg_cron 1.6.4 accepts the sub-minute interval syntax `'5 seconds'` (not just 5-field cron). It fired
on schedule: `cron.job_run_details` showed consecutive runs at `:00`, `:05`, `:10`, every one
`status='succeeded'`, `return_message='1 row'`. The documents went `pending → done` driven **purely by
cron** (no inline processor) — confirmed in the cron-only e

